# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2019-european-parliament-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-france] European Parliament elections were held in France for the first time on 10 June 1979.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-france] Four parties won seats: the centre right Union for French Democracy the Gaullist Rally for the Republic, the Socialist Party and the French Communist Party.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-ireland] The **1979 European Parliament election in Ireland** was the Irish component of the 1979 European Parliament election.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-ireland] These were the first direct elections to the European Parliament, and the first election to be held simultaneously across the entire Island of Ireland since the 1921 Irish elections.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-ireland] The election was conducted under the single transferable vote.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-ireland] Provisional Sinn Féin did not to contest the election.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-ireland] However, the relative success of Bernadette McAliskey in Northern Ireland helped prompt Sinn Féin to stand in subsequent European elections.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The **1979 European Parliament election in Italy** was held on 10 June 1979.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] As the 1979 Italian general election was held on 3 June, just a week before, the lack of matching between the two elections caused much controversy for wasting public money.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The pure party-list proportional representation was the traditional electoral system of the Italian Republic since its foundation in 1946, so it was naturally adopted to elect the Italian representatives to the European Parliament.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Two levels were used: a national level to divide seats between parties, and a constituency level to distribute them between candidates.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Italian regions were united in 5 constituencies, each electing a group of deputies.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] At national level, seats were divided between party lists using the largest remainder method with Hare quota.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] All seats gained by each party were automatically distributed to their local open lists and their most voted candidates.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] Seats are allocated to party lists on a national basis using an electoral quota, with the residue given to the lists with the largest excess over whole quotas.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] An electoral quota is then calculated for each list and used to allocate seats to each list in each of the five electoral regions.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] As the election took place just a week after the general election, it gave a similar result; however, the minor importance of the European ballot caused a lower turnout, which particularly punished the two major parties, Christian Democracy (DC) and the Italian Communist Party (PCI).
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-italy] The small Italian Liberal Party (PLI) had a breath of fresh air from this vote, doubling its percentage compared to seven days before.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] An election for Members of the European Parliament representing Netherlands constituency for the 1979–1984 term of the European Parliament was held on 7 June 1979.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] It was part of the wider 1979 European election.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] The ten seats were elected using proportional representation, with seats allocated using the D'Hondt method.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] The Labour Party and Political Party of Radicals formed an electoral alliance.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] Four parties were able to win seats: the conservative liberal VVD, the progressive liberal D66, the Christian-democratic CDA and the social-democratic Labour Party.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] Five other nationally represented parties compete but are unable to win seats.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-netherlands] 58.12% of the Dutch population turned out on election day.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The **1979 European Parliament election**, was the first European election to be held in the United Kingdom after the European Communities (EC) decided to directly elect representatives to the European Parliament.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Elections were also held in eight other EC states.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] European elections were incorporated into UK law by the European Assembly Elections Act 1978.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Out of the 410 members of the European Parliament, 81 were elected from the UK.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The electoral system was First past the post in England, Scotland and Wales (electing 78 MEPs in total) and Single Transferable Vote in Northern Ireland (electing 3 MEPs).
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] The result was a landslide victory for the Conservative Party, which won 60 of the 78 seats available in England, Wales and Scotland.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Their decisive victory in the general election of the previous month and divisions within the Labour party on whether to stay in the EC probably helped the Conservatives to such a comprehensive victory.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] There was a very low turnout in the election compared with other states, the lowest in Europe.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] Voter apathy was an explanation, but it is likely the large number of elections in 1979 had a significant negative effect on turnout.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-the-united-kingdom] There were referendums in Scotland and Wales on devolution in March and the general election in May, as well as local elections in England (not including London) and Wales.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-west-germany] An election of the delegation from West Germany to the first directly elected European Parliament was held in 1979.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-west-germany] The CDU/CSU won a plurality of the German seats in the European Parliament, which they retained in every subsequent election as of 2022.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election-in-west-germany] West Berlin, due to its special status, was ineligible to participate in the election.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The **1979 European Parliament election** was a series of parliamentary elections held across all 9 (at the time) European Community member states.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] They were the first European elections to be held, allowing citizens to elect 410 MEPs to the European Parliament, and also the first international election in history.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] Seats in the Parliament had been allocated to the states according to population, and in some cases were divided into constituencies, but members sat according to political groups.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The Treaty of Rome which established the Communities specified that the European Parliament must be elected by universal suffrage using a common voting system.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The Council of the European Union was responsible for setting up the elections but it had procrastinated.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] As a stop-gap measure, members were appointed to the Parliament by the member states from their own national parliaments, as they had done since the Common Assembly.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The Parliament was unhappy with this and threatened to take the Council to the European Court of Justice.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The Council eventually agreed to elections and the first European Parliament elections were held in 1979 after proposals were put forward in the mid-1970s.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The issue of a common voting method was left undecided, and even to this day the voting methods vary from member state to member state, although all have used some form of proportional representation since 1999.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The former Social Democrat German Chancellor Willy Brandt took an international campaign to France, Italy, Luxembourg and the Netherlands to boost the Socialist group.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] On the other hand, the former Prime Minister of France Jacques Chirac used the election to gauge his popularity against the then-President of France Valéry Giscard d'Estaing, in anticipation of a presidential bid in 1981.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] In June, the 410 members were elected by universal suffrage.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] At the time there were no rules on the system of election to be used.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The electorate took little interest but average voter turnout was 63%.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The lowest turn out was in the United Kingdom with 32.2%: all others were above 50% apart from Denmark.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] Aside from Belgium and Luxembourg, where voting is compulsory, the highest turnout was in Italy with 84.9%.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] Socialist parties working together under the Europe-wide Confederation of Socialist Parties won the most seats: the resultant Socialist group had 113 MEPs.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] Christian Democrat parties united within the pan-European European People's Party came second, with the resultant group having 107 MEPs.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The largest third force was the Conservative European Democrats with 64, followed by Communists with 44.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The Liberal Democrats had 40 seats, although their candidate was elected as President.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The groups formed were loose coalitions based on the groups founded in previous years, but they soon became the basis for modern European political parties.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] Louise Weiss, who was born in 1893 and thus 86 at the time, was found to be Parliament's oldest member and hence presided over the chamber while the election of the President took place (July 1979).
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] Before that could happen however, she immediately had to deal with Ian Paisley MEP who, in the first speech of the session, protested that the British flag outside the building was flying upside down.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] She dealt with the interruption swiftly.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The confrontation was seen as one of her finest hours and she later confided that, as a grandmother, she was used to dealing with "recalcitrant youngsters".
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] There were five candidates for President of the European Parliament: Giorgio Amendola, Italian Communist; Emma Bonino, Italian Technical Independent; Christian de La Malène, French Progressive Democrat; Simone Veil, French Liberal, and Mario Zagari, Italian Socialist.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] In the first ballot, Veil secured 183 of the 380 votes cast – eight short of the absolute majority needed.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The next closest contender was Zagari with 118 votes, then Amendola with 44, de la Malène with 26 and Bonino with 9.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] Bonino and de la Malène dropped out and Veil secured an absolute majority in the second ballot with 192 of the 377 votes cast (Zagari gained 128 and Amendola 47).
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] Veil was elected as the first President of the elected Parliament, and first female President of the Parliament since it was founded in 1952.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The following were elected as Vice-Presidents: Danielle De March, Basil de Ferranti, Bruno Friedrich, Guido Gonella, Gérard Jacquet, Hans Katzer, Poul Møller, Pierre Pflimlin, Bríd Rodgers, Marcel Albert Vandewiele, Anne Vondeling and Mario Zagari.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] Previously the Parliament was a weak consultative assembly, the members of which were part-time.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] With the elections the new body of MEPs were full-time, energetic and more diverse.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] As soon as the Parliament was established the "old guard" MEPs of the larger parties sought to raise the bar at which a European Parliament political group could be formed (the status gave financial support and representation in committees).
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] This move was quickly blocked by smaller groups working together and filibustering the proposal.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/1979-european-parliament-election] The ties formed at this time laid the foundations of the Rainbow group: an alliance of left-wing and green parties which later became the European Greens–European Free Alliance group.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The **2019 European Parliament election** was held in the European Union (EU) between 23 and 26 May 2019.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] It was the ninth parliamentary election since the first direct elections in 1979.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] A total of 751 Members of the European Parliament (MEPs) were elected to represent more than 512 million people from 28 member states.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] In February 2018, the European Parliament had voted to decrease the number of MEPs from 751 to 705 if the United Kingdom were to withdraw from the European Union on 29 March 2019.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] However, the United Kingdom participated alongside other EU member states after an extension of Article 50 to 31 October 2019; therefore, the allocation of seats between the member states and the total number of seats remained as it had been in 2014.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] On 26 May 2019, the centre-left and centre-right parties suffered significant losses, while pro-EU centrist, liberal and environmentalist parties and anti-EU right-wing populist parties made substantial gains.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The European People's Party led by Manfred Weber won the most seats in the European Parliament, making Weber the leading candidate to become the next President of the European Commission.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Despite this, the European Council decided after the election to nominate Ursula von der Leyen as new Commission President.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] On 7 June 2018, the Council agreed at ambassador level to change the EU electoral law and to reform old laws from the 1976 Electoral Act.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The purpose of the reform is to increase participation in elections, raise understanding of their European character and prevent irregular voting while at the same time respecting the constitutional and electoral traditions of the member states.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The reform forbids double voting and voting in third countries, thus improving the visibility of European political parties.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] To avoid double voting, contact authorities are established to exchange data on voters, a process that has to start at least six weeks before the elections.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The European Parliament gave its consent on 4 July 2018 and the Act was adopted by the Council on 13 July 2018.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] However, not all member states ratified the Act prior to the 2019 elections and therefore this election took place in line with the previous rules.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] This process was first used in 2014 and was opposed by some in the European Council.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The future of the process is uncertain, but the European Parliament has attempted to codify the process and the parties are almost certain to select the candidates again.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] In May 2018, a Eurobarometer poll suggested that 49% of the 27,601 individuals from all 28 EU countries surveyed think that the *Spitzenkandidat* process will help them vote in the next European elections while 70% also think that the process requires a real debate on European issues.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Incumbent Jean-Claude Juncker stated he would not seek a second term as President of the European Commission.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] At their 2018 Congress in Helsinki, the EPP elected Manfred Weber as their *Spitzenkandidat* for President of the European Commission.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Previous candidate Martin Schulz left the European Parliament in 2017 to head the Social Democratic Party of Germany, but he stepped down from the latter position in 2018.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Šefčovič announced his withdrawal in November and supported Frans Timmermans as the Common Candidate.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The party convened an extraordinary Congress in Lisbon to ratify the election of the candidate and to vote upon the manifesto.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Jan Zahradil, an MEP for the Czech Civic Democratic Party, is the *Spitzenkandidat* of the European Conservatives and Reformists.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] As in 2014, the Greens adopted the principle of having two leading candidates for the European Elections 2019.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Unlike in 2014, where the candidates were chosen through an open online primary elections, the two leading candidates were elected by the Council of the Party in Berlin in November 2018.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] At their 2018 Congress in Berlin, the party elected Ska Keller and Bas Eickhout as their *Spitzenkandidaten* for the President of the European Commission.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Oriol Junqueras, a Catalan historian, academic and former Vice President of Catalonia who, at the time of the election, was imprisoned because of his involvement in the 2017 Catalan independence referendum, was the *Spitzenkandidat* of the European Free Alliance.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The designated candidates are Violeta Tomič from Slovenia and Belgian trade-unionist Nico Cué.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The Europe of Freedom and Direct Democracy was widely expected to disband after the election.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] One reason was that its biggest share of MEPs came from the United Kingdom, which was long expected to leave the EU before the election.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The second was that the second-biggest partner, Italy's Five Star Movement (M5S), felt uneasy about this alliance anyway, having unsuccessfully tried to join the Greens/EFA or ALDE group instead.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] In February 2019, M5S alongside partners from Croatia, Finland, Greece and Poland presented a new alliance of anti-establishment parties that claim to be neither left nor right.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] In the 5-month period preceding the 2019 European Parliament elections, the blog byoblu.com, which collaborated with the Five Star Movement (M5S), published deceptive information on Twitter, spreading disinformation during the 2019 European elections.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The blog byoblu.com is owned by Claudio Messora, who was the head of communications for the 5 Star Movement and a close associate and friend of Beppe Grillo.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The Movement is an alliance of populist parties set up by Steve Bannon in 2018 with the purpose of contesting the European elections.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Participating parties included, at least temporarily, Lega Nord, People's Party of Belgium and Brothers of Italy and possibly French National Rally.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Originally envisioned as an attempt to unite the populist parties in Europe, The Movement has so far been snubbed by the Alternative for Germany, the Freedom Party of Austria and the UK Independence Party.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] In March 2019, reporters assessed Bannon's project as a failure.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Shortly ahead of the election, Marine Le Pen of the French National Rally distanced herself from Bannon, clarifying that he played no role in her party's campaign.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] In April 2019, Matteo Salvini of Italy's Lega launched the European Alliance of Peoples and Nations as a new coalition of populist, hard Eurosceptic and anti-immigration parties.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] It has been predicted to become the fourth largest group in parliament with an estimate of more than 80 MEPs.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] 2019 saw the debut of new parties such as Wiosna of Poland, Czech Pirate Party of Czech Republic, USR-PLUS of Romania, Human Shield and Most of Croatia, ĽSNS and Progressive Slovakia of Slovakia.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Some of the new parties have already joined European parties, e.g.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The new Brexit Party won 29 seats in the United Kingdom.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] As such, it won the most seats by any national political party in the parliament; the German CDU/CSU also won 29 seats but as an alliance.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The biggest new party after UK exit is La République En Marche!
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] (LREM) of French President Emmanuel Macron that was formed in 2016 and won the French presidential and parliamentary elections of the following year.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Initially, it balked at joining any of the existing party families, instead trying to form a new parliamentary group of pro-European centrists who support Macron's plans to reform the European institutions, drawing away members from ALDE, EPP, and S&D.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Possible partners for such a project were expected to include Spanish Ciudadanos, Progressive Slovakia, and the Hungarian Momentum Movement.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] However, the hypothetical group was considered to have difficulties to find MEPs from at least seven member states as is required to form a new group.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] In November 2018, LREM decided to cooperate with the liberal ALDE Group instead.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Nevertheless, Macron stressed that this was merely a loose alliance and his party is not a member of ALDE Party.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] He bluntly criticised ALDE for accepting donations from the Bayer-Monsanto chemical group while LREM's campaign chief threatened to recall the alliance.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] In April and May 2019, LREM continued its efforts to build a broader group, including ALDE, but also centrist and centre-left parties outside of ALDE.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The European Spring initiated from the Democracy in Europe Movement 2025 ran as a pan-European party alliance with one unified vision for Europe, the European Green New Deal.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The most prominent figure is the former Greek minister Yanis Varoufakis, who ran as a candidate in the constituency of Germany, but failed to secure a seat.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Despite garnering approximately one and a half million votes, no representatives who ran DiEM25 were elected, due to the votes being dispersed throughout different EU countries.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] As a new pan-European party, Volt Europa was founded in different European countries two years before the elections and successfully campaigned in eight EU countries for the elections with one transnational programme.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Despite missing its own goal to create a parliamentary group on its own, approximately half a million votes in total were sufficient to send one of the founders, Damian Boeselager, into the European Parliament via a German Volt list.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Since June 2019, Volt is part of the group of the Greens/EFA.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] In June 2018, the European Council decided to reapportion 27 of the 73 seats which would become vacant in the event of the United Kingdom leaving the EU.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] As the United Kingdom was still a member of the EU at the time of the election, the elections were held with the same allocation of seats as in 2014.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] When the United Kingdom left the EU, 27 of the seats were reallocated to other EU member states as shown below, resulting in a total of 705 MEPs.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The table below shows the changes in group composition after the United Kingdom left the EU.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Renew Europe replaced the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe group (ALDE) from the 2014−2019 Parliament.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] 198,255 votes for PS–SPOLU (Slovakia), which comprised parties which joined the RE and EPP groups, have been counted for the RE group.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] 1,252,139 votes for Ahora Repúblicas (Spain), which comprised parties which joined the G/EFA and GUE/NGL groups (plus one non-inscrit), have been counted for the G/EFA group.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Identity and Democracy largely replaced the Europe of Nations and Freedom (ENF) group from the 2014−2019 Parliament.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] 2,258,857 votes for Unidas Podemos Cambiar Europa (Spain), which comprised parties which joined the GUE/NGL and G/EFA groups, have been counted for the GUE/NGL group.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Geert Wilders, leader of the PVV, announced that the party would join the ID group.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] There were no pan-European polls for the European elections.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] However, several organisations calculated the theoretical seat distribution in the European Parliament based on national polls in all member states.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The table below displays these different projections.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] Since the United Kingdom notified its intention to leave the European Union in March 2017, the United Kingdom was expected not to participate in the European elections and was therefore excluded from projections.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] On 10 April 2019, the European Council extended the Brexit deadline to 31 October 2019, and the UK did participate in the European elections.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The UK was included in most projections after that date.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The following table shows projections with vote share instead of seats.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The heads of governments, gathered in a European Council on 1–3 July 2019, could not agree on a consensus President of the Commission.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The two *Spitzenkandidaten* were discussed, but neither Manfred Weber (EPP), nor Frans Timmermans (PES), who had the backing of many leaders but not of those from the Visegrád Group, had a majority.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] In the final hours of the vote, the name of Ursula von der Leyen was suggested and agreed to by all governments, with Germany's abstention.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The European Parliament elected Ursula von der Leyen as President of the European Commission on 16 July, with 383 votes in favour (374 votes needed).
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] The European Commission was approved by the European Parliament on 27 November 2019, receiving 461 votes, with 157 against and 89 abstentions.
[src:2019-european-parliament-election/2019-european-parliament-election] EPP, S&D, Renew Europe and half of the ECR voted in favour.
